If the State engage in and encourage foreign trade it will fail to get free of the competition which Socialists denounce, and must conform its agricultural policy to that of its competitore. If it set itself against it, it will be unable to seed a large population, and must be content to rule a poor and feeble nation. The land of Great Britain cannot yield food to half the people of Great Britain. In order that Britain may retain her place among the nations, it is absolutely neces· sary that her vast urban and manufacturing popula· tion should have cheap food, and therefore that the cultivators of the land should not receive high prices for its produce.
